An update on key personalities in the O.J. Simpson case: 

 *------ 

 SUPERIOR COURT JUDGE LANCE ITO: Simpson trial judge. Refuses all interviews. ``Keeping a low profile,'' he explains. Continues to preside over trials, recently allowed a camera into courtroom for sentencing.  

 JOHNNIE COCHRAN JR.: Simpson's lead attorney. Wrote book, ``Journey to Justice.'' Became host of cable TV shows, most recently ``Johnnie Cochran Tonight.'' Thriving law practice often focuses on cases where race at issue. Represents family of Haitian immigrant Abner Louima, who says he was tortured by New York police, and the family of 19-year-old Tyisha Miller, who was killed by police in Riverside, Calif.  

 BARRY SCHECK and PETER NEUFIELD: DNA specialists for Simpson. Also represent the Louima family and were called in to do DNA analysis in the unsolved JonBenet Ramsey case. Scheck represented British nanny Louise Woodward in 1997 child murder case.  

 ROBERT SHAPIRO: Simpson lawyer. Represents prominent clients, including New York Yankees outfielder Darryl Strawberry who hired him to negotiate contract settlement with Los Angeles Dodgers. Sued Strawberry for $100,000 plus interest in unpaid fees. Had a best seller with his book on the Simpson case, ``Search for Justice.''  

 F. LEE BAILEY: Simpson lawyer. Legendary defense attorney, practices in Boston and Palm Beach, Fla. Has had no high-profile case since Simpson. Jailed by a judge in 1996 in a dispute over his refusal to turn over $16 million that belonged to a client convicted of drug charges. Spent 43 days in jail and ordered to pay $423,737. Case is pending.  

 MARCIA CLARK: Former prosecutor. Received $4 million for her book, ``Without a Doubt,'' although sales did not meet expectations. No longer practices and is a regular guest host on the ``Rivera Live'' show on CNBC. Plans for her own television show fell through.  

 CHRISTOPHER DARDEN: Former prosecutor. Book, ``In Contempt,'' was a best seller. Recently co-wrote first novel, ``The Trials of Nikki Hill,'' a legal thriller. Teaches criminal law at Southwestern University Law School, is in private practice and has acted on several TV shows. Occasionally co-hosts the ``Rivera Live'' show.  

 MARK FUHRMAN: Former police detective. Wrote a book about the killings, ``Murder in Brentwood.'' Followed that with ``Murder in Greenwich,'' about a decades-old unsolved murder case. After the criminal trial, Fuhrman pleaded no contest to a perjury charge for denying he had used a racial epithet. Was sentenced to probation and fined $200. Lives in Sandpoint, Idaho, and hosts a Spokane, Wash., radio talk show about crime.  

 DENNIS FUNG: Criminalist. Criticized for sloppy handling of blood evidence, remains with the Los Angeles Police Department. Bungling of the investigation led to overhaul of forensic practices within the department.  

 BRIAN ``KATO'' KAELIN: The nation's most famous house guest. Lives in the Hollywood Hills and is still pursuing an acting career. Did a short stint on radio talk show. Has been seen at Hugh Hefner's Playboy mansion.  

 FAYE RESNICK: Ms. Simpson's close friend and occasional roommate. Wrote two books about the case, posed for ``Playboy,'' then left the public spotlight. Reportedly became an interior decorator and is engaged.  

 AL COWLINGS: O.J. Simpson's friend, fellow football star and driver of the Bronco during famed freeway chase. Most recently was working as a sales representative for a shoe and handbag company.  

 TOM LANGE and PHILIP VANNATTER: LAPD detectives. Retired at trial's end after writing book ``Evidence Dismissed,'' which was a best seller. Vannatter moved to an Indiana farm. Lange remains in Southern California.  

 FRED and PATTY GOLDMAN: Parents of murdered Ron Goldman. Moved to Scottsdale, Ariz. Goldman worked in the attorney general's office as a special assistant on victim's rights, but left that job in April to pursue a career in broadcasting. The Goldmans and their daughter, Kim, wrote a book, ``His Name Is Ron.''  

 LOUIS and JUDITHA BROWN: The parents of Nicole Brown Simpson. Locked in a protracted court battle with O.J. Simpson over the custody of Simpson's two younger children, Justin, 10, and Sydney, 13. Live in Orange County where Mrs. Brown is at work on a celebrity cookbook.  

 DENISE BROWN: Ms. Simpson's sister. Heads the Nicole Brown Charitable Foundation focusing on the plight of battered wives. Travels around the country speaking about domestic violence.  

 KATO, THE DOG: Nicole Brown Simpson's Akita dog whose howls on the night she was killed figured in the trial. Now lives with her parents in Orange County. The Simpson children play with him when they visit.  

